hristian martyr legend to elucidate the culture and society of late antique Iraq. Translated from Syriac into English here for the first time, the legend of Mar Qardagh introduces a hero of epic proportions whose characteristics confound simple classification. During the several stages of his career, Mar Qardagh hunts like a Persian King, argues like a Greek philosopher, and renounces his Zoroastrian family to live with monks high in the mountains of Iraqi Kurdistan. Drawing on both literary and artistic sources, Joel Walker explores the convergence of these diverse themes in the Christian culture of the Sasanian Empire (224-642). Taking the Qardagh legend as its foundation, his study guides readers through the rich and complex world of late antique Iraq.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNestorian ChurchzIraqxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aantiquity.  aarabic.  aarchaeology.  abyzantium.  achristian martyr.  achristianity.  acloister.  aconversion.  adevotion.  aepics.  afestival.  afolk narrative.  afolk tradition.  afolklore.  ahagiography.  ahero.  airaq.  akurdistan.  alegend.  amar qardagh.  amartyr cult.  amartyr.  amartyrdom.  amission.  amonasticism.  amonks.  amyth.  anestorian church.  anonfiction.  apersia.  apersian.  aphilosophy.  apiety.  arelics.  areligion.  areligious persecution.  asaint.  asasanian empire.  aspirituality.  atheology.  azoroastrianism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024578540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093219740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932197/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University o